{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ee69d791-c40a-4527-9ae2-445d18d56133","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so I'll give you the guidance directly.\n\nTo publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server tool.</Description>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key properties:**\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run |\n| `PackageId` | The NuGet package identifier |\n\n**Publish steps:**\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install & run with:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server\n```\n\nSince your server uses **stdio transport**, it works naturally as a dotnet tool — the host process spawns it and communicates over stdin/stdout. No additional transport configuration needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4dd0ab88-f41b-43f9-8d2b-1b8ad4bb0fab","outputTokens":411,"requestId":"3C09:1C1C65:1EE6A2D:22D531A:69E81DBD"},"id":"be1e10e5-72c3-4b39-8964-880e275086e0","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:00:53.072Z","parentId":"8e0150e0-e4ea-4d8e-a777-db1d2278faa6"}
